      <section class="detail-block">
        <h2>Application Scenarios</h2>
        <div class="scenario-list">
          <div class="scenario-item">
            <h3>Optical Film Roll Cleaning</h3>
            <p>Film rolls accumulate surface particles during winding, transport, and storage. When the roll is unwound for processing, these particles transfer to processing equipment and to the other film layers they contact. The Roll Chip Universal Cleaning Machine removes surface particles from optical film rolls before unwinding, preventing contamination propagation through the entire batch and protecting downstream processing equipment.</p>
          </div>
          <div class="scenario-item">
            <h3>Protective Film and Sheet Material Preparation</h3>
            <p>Protective films applied to display panels, glass substrates, and precision components during manufacturing and shipping must be free of particles on their adhesive surfaces. A particle trapped under a protective film during application scratches the protected surface when the film flexes or is removed. The Roll Chip Cleaner removes these particles before the protective film contacts the product surface.</p>
          </div>
          <div class="scenario-item">
            <h3>General-Purpose Flat Surface Cleaning</h3>
            <p>The universal design handles both roll stock and flat sheet materials, making it suitable as a flexible cleaning resource for production facilities that process multiple material types. Unlike product-specific cleaning machines, the Roll Chip Cleaner can be repositioned and reconfigured for different cleaning tasks without dedicated machinery for each substrate type.</p>
          </div>
        </div>
      </section>

      <section class="detail-block">
        <h2>When to Use a Universal Cleaner</h2>
        <p>The Roll Chip Universal Cleaning Machine is the right choice when you handle multiple film or sheet types that do not justify a dedicated cleaning machine for each, or when flexibility to handle new materials is a priority. For dedicated high-volume cleaning of a specific substrate — polarizer films, optical films of a specific width, PCBs, or LCM modules — a product-specific machine provides optimized performance and throughput. If you are unsure which approach fits your production, contact us with your material types and volumes for a recommendation.</p>
      </section>

      <section class="detail-block faq-block">
        <h2>Frequently Asked Questions</h2>
        <div class="faq-list">
          <div class="faq-item">
            <h3 class="faq-question">What types of materials can the Roll Chip Universal Cleaning Machine handle?</h3>
            <p class="faq-answer">The machine handles optical film rolls, thin sheet materials, protective films, and other flat or roll-format substrates used in display manufacturing and precision electronics. Its universal design accommodates a range of material types without requiring dedicated tooling for each substrate.</p>
          </div>
          <div class="faq-item">
            <h3 class="faq-question">How does the adhesive roller cleaning method work for roll materials?</h3>
            <p class="faq-answer">As the roll material unwinds or as sheet material passes through the machine, adhesive rollers contact the surface and lift particles away from the substrate. The adhesive roller captures particles without depositing any material onto the substrate — unlike brushing or blowing methods that redistribute particles rather than removing them.</p>
          </div>
          <div class="faq-item">
            <h3 class="faq-question">Does the machine include static elimination?</h3>
            <p class="faq-answer">Yes. Integrated intelligent static elimination is included, neutralizing electrostatic charge on the material surface simultaneously with particle removal. Film and sheet materials are particularly prone to electrostatic particle re-attraction, making simultaneous static elimination essential for effective cleaning.</p>
          </div>
          <div class="faq-item">
            <h3 class="faq-question">What is the quick-change window structure?</h3>
            <p class="faq-answer">The quick-change window structure allows the adhesive cleaning roller to be accessed and replaced without dismantling the machine housing. Routine maintenance is performed quickly between production runs, minimizing downtime.</p>
          </div>
          <div class="faq-item">
            <h3 class="faq-question">Is this machine suitable for use in a cleanroom?</h3>
            <p class="faq-answer">The Roll Chip Cleaner uses a sealed cleaning mechanism and generates no secondary particles from the cleaning process itself. Suitability for specific cleanroom classifications depends on your facility requirements — contact us to discuss cleanroom-compatible configurations.</p>
          </div>
          <div class="faq-item">
            <h3 class="faq-question">How does this compare to a dedicated polarizer or optical film cleaner?</h3>
            <p class="faq-answer">The Roll Chip Universal Cleaner provides flexible cleaning across multiple material types. Dedicated machines like the polarizer cleaner or STFK optical film cleaner are optimized for specific substrate dimensions, production speeds, and cleanliness requirements for their respective applications. If your production focuses primarily on one substrate type at high volume, a dedicated machine typically delivers better throughput and cleanliness performance.</p>
          </div>
        </div>
      </section>

